# Contributing

Thank you for considering contributing to this project! 🎉
Contributions of all kinds—bug fixes, new features, documentation improvements, and refactors—are welcome and appreciated.

This guide describes the expected workflow and standards to help keep contributions consistent and easy to review.

---

## Before You Start

Before making any changes, please:

- Read the project **README.md** for setup instructions and background context
- Search existing **issues** and **pull requests** to avoid duplicating work
- For larger or breaking changes, consider opening an issue first to discuss the approach

---

## GitHub settings (maintainers)

If you maintain this repository on GitHub, configure **branch protection** and **merge
settings** on the default branch (usually `main`) so changes use pull requests and (as
recommended here) **squash merge** only. See
[`.github/github-branch-protection.md`](.github/github-branch-protection.md) for the full
checklist.

Contributors should always open pull requests against the default branch and avoid pushing
directly to it.

---

## Getting Started

### 1. Fork the Repository

Create a fork of the repository on GitHub.

### 2. Create a Feature Branch

Create a new branch with a descriptive name:

```bash
git checkout -b feature/short-description
```

### 3. Set Up the Development Environment

```bash
uv sync --frozen --extra dev --extra test{% if include_docs %} --extra docs{% endif %}{% if include_git_cliff %} --group changelog{% endif %}
just precommit-install
```

`just precommit-install` registers pre-commit, pre-push, and **commit-msg** hooks (Conventional Commits), and points Git’s **commit template** at the repository `.gitmessage` file so your editor opens with a short scaffold. Pull request titles should use the same convention when you expect a **squash merge** (the title is often the default squash commit subject). CI validates PR title, body, and branch commits via the **PR policy** workflow when it is enabled as a required check.

---

## Testing

All changes must be tested.

- Run the full test suite locally:
  ```bash
  just test
  ```

- Add or update tests for:
  - New features
  - Bug fixes
  - Any change that affects behavior

Pull requests with failing or missing tests will not be merged.

---

## Code Style and Quality

This project enforces automated formatting and linting.

Before submitting your changes, run:

```bash
just fmt    # ruff format
just lint   # ruff lint
just type   # basedpyright type check
```

Ensure that:

- Code is properly formatted
- Linting issues are resolved
- Type hints and docstrings are added where appropriate

---

## Making Changes

When working on your contribution:

- Keep commits **small and focused**
- Follow existing patterns and project structure
- Avoid unrelated refactors or formatting-only changes
- Write clear and descriptive commit messages

---

## Submitting a Pull Request

1. Push your branch to your fork
2. Open a pull request against the main repository
3. In the pull request description:
   - Clearly explain what the change does
   - Reference related issues (for example, `Closes #123`)
   - Call out any breaking changes or follow-up work

Maintainers may request changes or clarifications before merging.

---

## Pull Request Checklist

Before submitting your pull request, confirm that:

- [ ] Tests pass locally
- [ ] New functionality includes appropriate tests
- [ ] Code follows project style and conventions
- [ ] Documentation has been updated if needed
- [ ] The pull request is scoped to a single logical change

---

## Code of Conduct

By participating in this project, you agree to follow the project’s **Code of Conduct**.
Please help maintain a respectful, inclusive, and welcoming environment for everyone.

---

Thank you for contributing and helping improve the project! 🚀
